article.description: Becky Hammon scored 18 of her 22 points in the second half to lead the Liberty past the Sparks 74-69 Wednesday night in New York.
article.headline: Sparks fall a game outside fourth spot in West
article.linkText: Hammon, Liberty gain first season sweep of L.A.
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Becky Hammon made sure the New York Liberty
finally played a strong game, from start to finish.

Hammon scored 18 of her 22 points in the second half, leading
the Liberty over the Los Angeles Sparks 74-69 Wednesday night.

"The issue this year has been putting a 40-minute game together
and we did that through the buzzer tonight," Hammon said. "That's
a quality team. They have veterans and Olympians. Had we let up for
one or two minutes, this game could have been another story."

Ann Wauters had 18 points and Elena Baranova added 15 points and
nine rebounds for New York (14-13), which swept a season series
from Los Angeles for the first time. The Liberty also moved within
a half-game of third-place Washington in the Eastern Conference.

"We did a great job on the offensive boards, getting them off
the boards in the second half," Hammon said. "Even so, they still
go off 12 more shots than us."

The Liberty shot 44 percent (21-for-48) and outrebounded Los
Angeles 32-31. New York, the WNBA's top free-throw-shooting team,
was 81 percent (25-for-31) from the line.

Chamique Holdsclaw had 21 points and 13 rebounds, and Lisa
Leslie scored 18 points for the Sparks (12-15), who finished 2-6 on
their season-high eight-game road trip. Los Angeles has lost eight
of 10 overall, falling one game behind Minnesota and Phoenix for
fourth place in the West.

The Sparks were 13 for 22 on free throws, missing six of 14 in
the second half.

"We played a very good team tonight, on their home court," Los
Angeles coach Henry Bibby said. "Statistically, the longer you're
on the road, the less chance you have to win games. We missed some
free throws, a couple of layups late in the game. They made a
couple of big shots."

Trailing by six points, the Sparks had an 8-1 run to take a
61-60 lead with 3:11 remaining. Holdsclaw had five points during
the run, including the go-ahead layup.

Baranova hit a 3-pointer 22 seconds later to regain the lead for
New York, and Leslie's jump hook tied it at 63 with 2½ minutes
left.

After Wauters made a layup for the Liberty, Laura Macchi hit a 3
to give Los Angeles a 66-65 lead with 1:42 remaining.

Wauters hit a pair of free throws and made a layup to give New
York a three-point lead with 48.5 seconds to go.

Christi Thomas then missed two free throws 13 seconds later, and
Hammon made one of two, and Baranova hit two to push the Liberty's
lead to 72-66 with 14.4 seconds left.

"We've been playing better team basketball," Holdsclaw said.
"It's just the little things. We have to cut down on some of our
turnovers, play better defense."

Doneeka Hodges hit a 3 with 8.6 seconds remaining, but Hammon
made a pair of free throws 5 seconds later to seal New York's win.

After scoring just four points on 0-for-2 shooting with one
assist in the first half, Hammon was 5-for-9 with five assists
after the break.

"She understood in the first half how they were guarding her,
and what was open in the second half," Liberty coach Pat Coyle
said. "She made terrific decisions, unbelievable passes to our
bigs. Her decision-making was terrific."

Hammon's three-point play gave New York its first lead of the
second half, 45-44 with 13:34 left.

Thomas made a free throw to tie it for Los Angeles. The Liberty
had a 10-4 surge, capped by Hammon's second 3 of the stretch to
take a 55-49 lead with 8:01 remaining.

Los Angeles led 32-29 at the break.

New York went on a 10-1 spurt, capped by a pair of free throws
by Vickie Johnson, to take a 29-25 lead with just over 2½ minutes
left in the first half.

The Sparks scored the last seven points before the break. Macchi
had a 3-pointer, made one of two free throws and Hodges hit a
tiebreaking 3 with .6 seconds left.

Holdsclaw scored Los Angeles' first nine points and finished the
half with 12.
